        {
          "id": 18631,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Miasma Theory </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18632,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Germ Theory </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18633,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Web of causation theory </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18634,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Epidemiological Wheel theory</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">A microbiology student is studying the principles of pathogen identification and comes across Henle-Koch&rsquo;s postulates. These postulates were formulated to establish a causative relationship between a specific microorganism and a specific disease. Which of the following best describes the central philosophy of Henle-Koch&#39;s postulates?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q6815152",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34077,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        7
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B. Germ Theory</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Germ Theory</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: <strong>Each and every disease</strong> is caused by a <strong>microbe or germ</strong>. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Henle Koch&#39;s postulates -&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">First formulated by the <strong>German pathologist Friedrich Gustav Jacob Henle</strong> (1809&ndash;1885) and <strong>adapted and modified</strong> by the <strong>German bacteriologist Robert Koch</strong> (1843&ndash;1910), these are four criteria that usually suffice to confirm the causal relationship of a pathogenic organism to a specific infectious disease. The postulates are - </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The agent must be demonstrable in every case of the disease;&nbsp;</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The agent is not present in other diseases;&nbsp;</span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">After isolation in culture, the agent must be able to produce the disease in experimental animals; and </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The agent can be recovered from the experimental animal&nbsp;(added by Koch)&nbsp;</span></span></span></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation</span></u></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option A.&nbsp;Miasma Theory:</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> <strong>Human diseases</strong> are due to <strong>bad air</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option C.&nbsp;Web of causation theory</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: <strong>Various factors</strong> interact like <strong>web to cause disease.</strong> </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option D.&nbsp;Epidemiological wheel theory:&nbsp;</span></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Visualizes human disease</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"> in <strong>form of wheel</strong> with <strong>central hub</strong> and <strong>spoke</strong> which are contributed by various factors. </span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective</span></u></strong><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\">Robert Koch</span></span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"color:black\"> was a distinguished <strong>German microbiologist;</strong> <strong>Koch&#39;s legacy</strong> lies in the <strong>germ theory</strong>. He is <strong>famed for determining the pathogens</strong> responsible for <strong>tuberculosis, cholera</strong>, and <strong>anthrax</strong> and for <strong>devising Koch&#39;s postulates.</strong></span></span></span></span></p>",
