    {
      "id": 4689,
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 18731,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Predisposing factor</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18732,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Enabling factor</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18733,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Precipitating factor</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18734,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Reinforcing factor.</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">In the context of public health, factors that facilitate the development of a disease or aid in recovery from an illness are crucial for understanding health outcomes. These factors can either expose individuals to higher risk or enhance their ability to cope and recover. Which term best describes these elements?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q5949351",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34074,
      "difficulty_level": "difficult",
      "subjects_id": [
        7
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">Ans. B. Enabling factor</span></strong>&nbsp; </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">Option B:</span></span></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">Enabling factors&nbsp;</span></strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">are those which <strong>assist in the development of </strong>(or in recovery from) the <strong>disease</strong>; e.g. housing conditions, socio-economic status.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><u><strong>Explanation</strong></u>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option A. Predisposing factors:</strong>&nbsp;Factors which <strong>create a state of susceptibility</strong>, so that the <strong>host becomes vulnerable </strong>to the <strong>agent </strong>or to necessary cause, e.g. age, sex, previous illness.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option C. Precipitating factors:</strong>&nbsp;Are those that are <strong>associated with immediate exposure </strong>to the <strong>disease agent </strong>or onset of disease, e.g. drinking contaminated water, close contact with an open case of pulmonary TB.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option D. Reinforcing factors: </strong>Are those which <strong>aggravate an already existing disease</strong>, e.g. malnutrition, repeated, exposures, etc.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u>:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Enabling factors </strong>specifically refer to <strong>conditions that facilitate the development of a disease </strong>or <strong>support the recovery process</strong>, which can be essential for <strong>designing effective health interventions </strong>and <strong>recovery programs</strong>.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><u>Ref</u>: AFMC Red Book pg 20</span></strong></span></span></p>",
