    {
      "id": 4694,
      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 18751,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Risk factor</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18752,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Predisposing factor </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18753,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Risk Marker </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18754,
          "text": "<p><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">Enabling factor</span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">A 54-year-old man presents to the clinic for a routine check-up. The physician notices the presence of a well-defined transverse crease on the patient&rsquo;s earlobe. The physician recalls that this physical finding has been associated with an increased risk of ischemic heart disease (IHD) in many studies. The development of a transverse crease on the earlobe is considered a ?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1756654",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34075,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        7
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">Ans. C. Risk Marker.</span></strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option C</strong>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Risk marker </strong>is <strong>surrogate </strong>or a <strong>proxy indicator </strong>of the <strong>risk of the disease</strong>, mostly because of it&rsquo;s <strong>association with another risk factor</strong>.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">This is known as&nbsp;</span><strong>Frank&#39;s sign</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><u><strong>Explanation</strong></u>:</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option A. Risk factor:</strong>&nbsp;A <strong>condition</strong>, <strong>quality </strong>or <strong>attribute</strong>, the <strong>presence of which increases </strong>the <strong>chances of an individual </strong>to have, <strong>develop </strong>or be adversely affected by a disease process.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option B.&nbsp;Predisposing factors:</strong>&nbsp;Factors which <strong>create a state of susceptibility</strong>, so that the <strong>host </strong>becomes <strong>vulnerable </strong>to the agent or to necessary cause.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><strong>Option D.&nbsp;Enabling factors:</strong>&nbsp;Are those which <strong>assist in the development </strong>of (or in recovery from) the <strong>disease</strong>, e.g. housing conditions, socio-economic status.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u>:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><br />\r\n<span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong>Recognize </strong>that the <strong>development of a transverse crease </strong>on the <strong>earlobe </strong>is considered a <strong>risk marker for ischemic heart disease</strong>, indicating an association with <strong>increased risk </strong>but <strong>not establishing a definitive diagnosis </strong>or causal relationship.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><u>Ref</u>: Textbook of Community Medicine by Rajvir Balwar 2<sup>nd</sup> Ed pg 20.</span></strong></span></p>",
