        {
          "id": 18755,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It considers all the predisposing factors and their complex inter relationship with each other. </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18756,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Removal or elimination of just one major link that is sufficiently important in pathogenic process is sufficient to control disease.</span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18757,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It shows the possible interventions that can be taken to reduce the occurrence of disease. </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 18758,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It implies that, at all instances, all the chains of causation must be controlled to prevent the disease.</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">A public health expert is educating a group of medical students about various models used to understand the complexity of disease causation. He introduces the concept of the &quot;web of causation,&quot; then presents a list of characteristics related to it and asks the students to identify which statement does NOT accurately describe this model?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2254566",
      "question_audio": null,
