      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\">Ans. D.&nbsp;It implies that individual facts in the chain have equal weightage and all the chains of causation must be controlled to prevent the disease. </span></span></strong></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><u><strong>Explanation:</strong></u></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">Model <strong>&quot;Web of causation&quot; </strong>- proposed by <strong>McMohan and Pugh</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:#000000\">The <strong>web of causation </strong>considers all the <strong>predisposing factors </strong>and their <strong>complex interrelationship with each other</strong>. This <strong>model is ideally suited </strong>to <strong>study chronic disease</strong>. The web of causation does not imply that the disease is controlled only when all the multiple chains of causation are removed.&nbsp;</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">For <strong>preventing a disease</strong>, it is not necessary to <strong>take action against all the factors </strong>-identifying the <strong>&ldquo;weakest links&rdquo; </strong>in the <strong>inter-lacing webs</strong>, <strong>actions directed </strong>to these <strong>weakest links </strong>may be of considerable <strong>value in prevention.</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><span style=\"color:#000000\"><img src=\"https://lh7-us.googleusercontent.com/i9r4SEVFrbnH3A2dgRjd3YdIcT_RcsHulfV6DHBAvD14ztE1Q_NDpt-fmM8wkmZrtU2VuUWXJXhAEylv4L62dDS0-jZoQbKWXO9mc3UK2ep3HyaJzNMAo5rWulUSMl2foiyoVh80JGMpdCVxcdLTIVI\" style=\"height:280px; width:399px\" /></span></span><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><u>Educational Objective</u>:</strong></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\">The educational objective is to understand the <strong>&quot;web of causation&quot; model </strong>in <strong>public health</strong>, which is used to describe the <strong>complex </strong>and <strong>interconnected factors </strong>leading to the <strong>development of diseases</strong>. This <strong>model highlights </strong>that <strong>disease prevention</strong> and <strong>intervention </strong>can be <strong>multifaceted </strong>and does not require the control of all factors, challenging the simplistic linear chain of causation approach.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:16px\"><strong><span dir=\"ltr\" lang=\"EN-US\"><u>Ref</u>: Park 26<sup>th</sup> ed pg 41.</span></strong></span></p>",
